  content:
    '<div class="paragraph">\n<p>Natural language has the risk that semantics on the sender&#8217;s side differs from semantics of the receiver: People simply misunderstand each other because the <em>meaning</em> of words differs between people.</p>\n</div>\n<div class="paragraph">\n<p>Therefore: what people mean/want/need is sometimes not what they say. This is due either to</p>\n</div>\n<div class="ulist">\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p>semantic differences on sender and receive sides,</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>stressful or inconvenient communication situations (e.g. "the boss is present", communication under pressure),</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>people are distracted or tired,</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class="paragraph">\n<p>or other reasons.</p>\n</div>\n<div class="paragraph">\n<p>NLP (neurolingustic programming) practitioners recommend to <em>mirror</em> things you hear to your communication partners in your own words. This might facilitate understanding.</p>\n</div>\n<div class="paragraph">\n<p>When you have the slightest impression or indicator that your communication partner does not or can not communicate their real intention, you should\nclarify by giving explicit <a href="#Fast-Feedback">Section 5.11, &#8220;<span class="pattern">Fast Feedback</span>&#8221;</a>.</p>\n</div>'
